  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Initial efforts to combat such activities emerged in the 1930s\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States\n- First comprehensive legislation targeting financial reporting\n- Required banks to report cash transactions over $10,000\n- Established recordkeeping requirements\n- Aimed at combating organized crime and tax evasion\n\n3. International Developments\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global problem\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating financial crimes\n\n4. Key Legislative Milestones\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act (US)\n- Made money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Established comprehensive legal framework\n- 1992: International Money Laundering Prevention Act\n\n5. Global Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Framework\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- Palermo Convention\n- Basel Committee Guidelines\n- Expanded international cooperation and standardization\n\n6. Post-9/11 Developments\n- Patriot Act (2001)\n- Enhanced financial transparency requirements\n- Strengthened counter-terrorism financing measures\n\nThese developments represent a progressive legal approach to preventing financial crimes.",
